t2656.text: But ultimately I just want people to be kinder to themselves, to break the guilt/shame cycle, to stop listening to celebrities and influencers about diet and exercise, to stop beating themselves into the ground with workouts in order to feel they have earned the right to eat.

t2657.text: Find activities you LIKE TO DO and fuel that performance. Sleep more and better. You are allowed to rest if you're tired (if anything you should rest if you're tired). Add more veggies and protein into your eating habits.

t2658.text: But do it from a place of treating your body with kindness. Know that one meal, one ice cream, one feasting will have no hating on progress. You do not need to beat yourself up for enjoying food and eating. Start in small ways. Don't overhaul your life for the scale.

t2659.text: Diet culture suggest we should suffer and hate ourselves in order to earn the right to like ourselves and that is FUCKED UP. But if you want to lose weight to be more comfortable or confident you are also allowed to do that.

t2660.text: That not going to the gym while working or studying or raising a family is not a failure. That if you find the classes a chore that that is okay. That you don't need to get beat down in order for it to be exercise. WALKING IS A VERY VALID FORM OF EXERCISE.

t2661.text: But I'm here to tell you that not losing weight is not a failure and your weight does not your worth. That a diet is not dogmatic and not adhering to it is a failure on diet culture not you because they are designed to fail.

t2662.text: But this is diet culture speaking. This idea that you're never enough and you should hate your body. To be so vulnerable to buy into shitty diets like Keto or shakes or whatever else that Facebook group has been spruking. This idea that you somehow failed by not losing weight.

t2663.text: Going into 2020 hating your body is no way to live. Especially if you've done it every year. I always feel sad about the "this year I will finally lose (insert random number here) kg/lbs!" Resolutions because I have been there. Year after year.
